      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan amortization table and i'm confused. i've been making the same monthly payment for a year now but the principal balance is barely moving. why is the balance decreasing so slowly even though i'm paying the same amount every month?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow-moving principal balance is a common sight in the world of student loans, and it's not just you. It's like trying to move a boulder with a feather; the payment you're making is like that feather, and the principal balance is that boulder. The reason your balance is barely moving is that a significant portion of your payment is going towards the interest on the loan, not directly reducing the principal. It's like paying the rent to the landlord (the interest) while the boulder (the principal) stays put. Over time, as the interest rate decreases, you'll see more of your payment going towards the principal, and the boulder will start to move. But for now, keep at it, and soon you'll see the boulder start to shift.",
