    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the landlord thing but can you explain the actual math behind it? like, how does the interest calculation work each month if the principal isn't dropping much? i'm trying to understand the formula being used.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! Let's dive into the math behind the slow-moving principal balance, shall we? Imagine your student loan as a magical goblin forest. Each month, the goblins (interest) gather around and take a little bit of your gold (monthly payment) to keep their homes (the loan balance) cozy. The amount they take depends on the size of your gold and the interest rate set by the goblin council (the loan terms).\n\nHere's a simplified version of the formula they use:\n\nInterest for the month = (Principal balance) x (Monthly interest rate)\n\nNow, let's say you have a principal balance of $10,000 and a monthly interest rate of 1%. The goblins would take $100 of your gold each month for interest. If your monthly payment is $300, then $200 goes towards the principal, and $100 goes towards the interest.\n\nSo, your new principal balance would be $9,800 ($10,000 - $200). But the goblins are clever; they know that the smaller the boulder (principal balance), the less gold (interest) they'll take the next month. As the principal balance decreases, the interest portion of your payment also decreases, and more of your gold goes towards reducing the",
